==Old English==
===Etymology===
From Germanic ''*skeutanan'', from Indo-European ''*(s)keud-''.  Cognate with Old Frisian [[skiata]], Old Saxon [[skiotan]] (Dutch [[schieten]]), Old High German [[skiozan]] (German [[schießen]]), Old Norse [[skjóta]] (Swedish [[skjuta]]).  The PIE root is also the source of Old Church Slavonic [[искыдати]] (Russian [[кидать]]), Lithuanian [[skudrùs]].

===Pronunciation===
{{IPA|/ˈʃeːotan/}}

===Verb===
'''scēotan''' (class II strong: ''3 singular present'' '''[[sciett|scīett]]''', ''3 singular preterite'' '''[[sceat|scēat]]''', ''preterite plural'' '''[[scuton]]''', ''past participle'' '''[[scoten]]''')
# ''(transitive)'' to [[shoot]], throw a missile
# ''(transitive)'' to [[push]], move quickly, pay (money)
# ''(intransitive)'' to move quickly, [[flow]], [[rush]], [[shoot]] (of pain)

